🔹Step 1:Questions
some meaningful questions we might ask:

Does GRE Score strongly affect the Chance of Admit?

Which matters more — TOEFL Score or CGPA?

Do LOR/Recommendation Strength and SOP Strength influence admissions?

Are there outliers (like very high GRE but low admit chance)?

🔹Step 2: Explore Data Structure
import pandas as pd

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_excel("Admission_Predict.xls")

# Basic info
print(df.info())
print(df.head())


👉 This shows:

Number of rows/columns

Data types (int, float, object)

Sample data

🔹 Step 3: Summary Statistics
print(df.describe())


This gives:

Mean, Median, Min, Max, Std for each variable

Helps find extreme values (outliers)

🔹 Step 4: Detect Missing or Bad Data
print(df.isnull().sum())


👉 This checks if any values are missing.

🔹 Step 5: Identify Trends & Patterns
GRE vs Admission Chance
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.scatter(df["GRE Score"], df["Chance of Admit "])
plt.xlabel("GRE Score")
plt.ylabel("Chance of Admit")
plt.title("GRE vs Chance of Admit")
plt.show()

CGPA vs Admission Chance
plt.scatter(df["CGPA"], df["Chance of Admit "])
plt.xlabel("CGPA")
plt.ylabel("Chance of Admit")
plt.title("CGPA vs Chance of Admit")
plt.show()


👉 You’ll likely see that higher GRE/CGPA → higher Chance of Admit.

🔹 Step 6: Test Hypotheses (Statistics)

Example Hypothesis:
💡 “Higher GRE scores increase the chance of admission.”

We can check correlation:

correlation = df.corr()
print(correlation["Chance of Admit "].sort_values(ascending=False))


👉 This shows which features have the strongest relationship with admission chances.

🔹 Step 7: Detect Data Issues

Things to look for:

Any duplicate rows? → df.duplicated().sum()

Any weird values (like GRE < 200, CGPA > 10)?

Are all values in realistic ranges?

🔹 Step 8: Visualization (Big Picture)
import seaborn as sns

# Correlation Heatmap
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()


